Part 1. Code up a DGP in which there are \(n_t\) observations of \(n_i\) individual economic agents (i.e., an \(n_i \times n_t\) panel). Within this panel, allow some but not all \(i\) to be treated. For now, assume that treatment falls in the middle of the time series, at the same \(t\) for each treated unit—once treatment arrives, let’s have treatment stay on for the rest of the time series (for now, anyway). Likewise, have all \(i\) trend similarly through the time series. (You should recognize that this is all sounding fairly well behaved—the sort of environment in which we would expect to be able to identify the causal parameter.) Here’s the twist. As part of this DGP, I don’t want you to hardwire \(i\) specific trends to be common—instead, have each cross-sectional unit draw their trend from a \(N(0,\sigma)\) distribution. In this way, we would expect that they would be trending similarly on average, but we could questions this somewhat. (Hence, parameterize the variance so you can consider its role.)


The DGP:

# description of parameters
# difference between treatment and control group: beta_x = 1
# diff between treated and untreated period: beta_tr = 0
# effect of treatment in treated period: beta_xtr = 1
# effect of time/year - linear: beta_t = 0
# heterogeneous effect of time in treated period: beta_ttr = 0
# effect of cluster-level variable: beta_cx = 0

simulate_panel <- function(seed = 1, n_i, n_c, n_t){
  
cross <- tibble(
    i = 1:n_i,
    # assignment to treatment
    x = rep(0:1, each = n_i/2),
    # cluster in which y belongs
    c = sample(1:n_c,size = n_i, replace = T),
    # length of the panel
    t_length = n_t,
    # individual-level error term
    ei = rnorm(length(1:n_i), 0, 1)
)

cluster <- tibble(
    c = 1:n_c,
    # cluster-level variable
    cx = rnorm(n_c),
    # cluster-level error term
    ec = rnorm(length(1:n_c), 0, 1)
)

year <- tibble(
    t = 1:n_t,
    # year-level error term
    et = rnorm(length(1:n_t), 0, 1)
)

panel <- plyr::ddply(cross, ~i, transform, t = 1:t_length) %>%
  left_join(cluster, by = "c") %>%
  left_join(year, by = "t") %>%
  mutate(
    eit = rnorm(length(1:(n_i*n_t)), 0, 1),
    tr = ifelse(t>=n_t/2, 1, 0),
    xtr = x*tr,
     # with four error terms and only x and xtr turned on
    y1 = 10 + 1*x + 0*tr + 1*xtr + 0*t + 0*t*tr + 0*cx + eit + et + ei + ec,
    # with tr turned on
    y2 = 10 + 1*x + 1*tr + 1*xtr + 0*t + 0*t*tr + 0*cx + eit + et + ei + ec,
    # with t turned on
    y3 = 10 + 1*x + 0*tr + 1*xtr + 1*t + 0*t*tr + 0*cx + eit + et + ei + ec,
    # with t*tr turned on
    y4 = 10 + 1*x + 0*tr + 1*xtr + 0*t + 1*t*tr + 0*cx + eit + et + ei + ec,
    # with cx turned on
    y5 = 10 + 1*x + 0*tr + 1*xtr + 0*t + 0*t*tr + 1*cx + eit + et + ei + ec,
    # with all things turned on
    y6 = 10 + 1*x + 1*tr + 1*xtr + 1*t + 1*t*tr + 1*cx + eit + et + ei + ec
  )

return(panel)
}



Part 2: Plot a representative iteration of the above DGP, clearly demonstrating (i) where treatment falls and (ii) which observations are part of the treatment group and which are part of the control groups. (I’m asking for the classic DiD plot, showing trends across time and any level shift induced by treatment.)

# setting time, individual, cluster parameters (n)
n_t <- 20
n_i <- 100
n_c <- 10

panel <- simulate_panel(n_i = n_i, n_c = n_c, n_t = n_t)

gen_did_plot <- function(df, y_outcome, caption){
  
  plot <- ggplot(df, aes(x = t, y = {{y_outcome}}, color = factor(x))) +
  geom_line(aes(group = i), alpha = 0.1) +
  geom_smooth(data = filter(panel, t < n_t/2), method = "lm", linewidth = 1) +
  geom_smooth(data = filter(panel, t >= n_t/2), method = "lm", linewidth = 1) +
  labs(
    x = "Time",
    y = "Outcome",
    color = "Treatment Group",
    caption = paste0(caption,
                    "\n", max(df$i)," individual-level data for ",max(df$t)," time-periods across ",max(df$c)," clusters.\nMean size of cluster: ",mean(table(df$c)/n_t)
)
  ) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = 1:n_t)+
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = (n_t-1)/2), color = "darkred", linetype = "dotted")+
  annotate(geom = "text", x = n_t/2 - 0.8, y = 15, label = "Time of treatment",color = "darkred", angle = 90, size = 3, alpha = 0.7)+
  scale_color_manual(values = rev(RColorBrewer::brewer.pal(4, "Dark2"))) +
  theme_classic() +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom") #+
    #scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0,20))
  
  plot
}

Part 3. Simulate this DGP, demonstrating that the distribution of \(\hat\beta\) across 500 iterations of your DGP well captures the true \(\beta=1\), given the estimating equation, \[Y_{it}= \alpha_0 + \alpha_1~X_i + \alpha_2~T_t + \beta~X_iT_t + e_{it}~.\]

The simulation:

# Number of iterations
n_iter <- 500

# List of dgp
dgp_list <- map(1:n_iter, ~simulate_panel(seed = .x, n_i = n_i, n_c = n_c, n_t = n_t))

dgp_est <- function(seed, dgp_df){
  
 estimates <- map_df(
    c("y1", "y2", "y3", "y4", "y5", "y6"),
    ~ lm_robust(
      formula = as.formula(paste0(.x, " ~ x + tr + xtr")),
      data = dgp_df,
      se_type = "CR2",
      clusters = i
    ) %>%
      tidy() %>%
      filter(term == "xtr")
  ) %>%
    mutate(seed = seed)

  return(estimates)
}


# get estimates
estimate_df <- map_df(1:length(dgp_list), ~dgp_est(seed = .x, dgp_df = dgp_list[[.x]]))
